<TITLE> Minister for national plan against industrial pollution </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 8 (bdnews24.com)  A national-level initiative is needed to prevent industrial pollution that has posed a severe threat to the environment, said the state minister for forests and environment on Sunday. "Industrial wastes from the mills and factories have become looming factors in environmental disasters," Mostafizur Rahman told parliament in reply to questions from Sarah Begum Kobori MP and Benazir Ahmed MP. "A national-level scheme is needed to prevent the pollution." Replying to Fazle Rabbi Miah MP, the state minister said, "Red notices will be served on the units failing to set up waste treatment plants in time, but the parliament must back that move." 10 Boeing aircrafts to be bought The government has taken steps to purchase 10 Boeing aircrafts, civil aviation and tourism minister GM Quader told the House in answer to separate questions from Awami League MP Sheikh Fazlul Karim and Jatiya Party MP Golam Kibria,. "We'll be tough on anyone if found at fault in the deal signed with Boeing," he warned. The minister said that eight of ten aircrafts of state-carrier Bangladesh Biman Airlines were currently in operation. Fertiliser dealership not flawless Agricuture minister Motia Chowdhury, in reply to a question by AL MP Mojibur Rahman Fakir, told parliament that the present fertiliser dealership system "is not flawless". "But the system will remain unchanged throughout the peak season until March." "The government has planned a series of measures including making the system easier and fertilisers available to all farmeers at subsidised rates," she said. The agriculture minister said 1.5 lakh metric tonnes of urea was being imported to avert any possible crisis. bdnew
